images.title: Mahabalipuram
images.description:
The expats call this place Mahabs.

On the coast of the Bay of Bengal, one hour south of Chennai

images.title: Shore Temple
images.description:
Shore Temple

The big site in Mahabs - Unesco certified, etc.

A granite temple, built 700AD, sits on a a raised spit of land, overlooking the beach. Marco Polo used it as a navigation landmark.

images.title: Butterball!
images.description:
Butterball!

The second main site in Mhabalipuram. The official name is “Vaan Irai Kal,” which translates to “Sky God’s Stone."

But everybody calls it Krishna's Butterball.

images.title: Temples above Butterball
images.description:
Temples above Butterball

There's about a mile of paths through the rocks in this area, connecting about 10 stone temples.

images.title: Temple
images.description: At the northern edge of the Butterball district.

images.title: Where do they go?
images.description:
Where do they go?

Answer: basically nowhere. We got a little lost up there, and had to climb down some awkward rock faces.

images.title: _DSC1327
images.description: Sarah Chills, or recovers from chills.  She is about two days recovered from a terrible flu.

images.title: Catholics
images.description:
Catholics

We hit these temples at about 5PM, and they were still pretty packed with sight-seers, including a lot of Catholic school girls.

images.title: All Architectures Welcome!
images.description:
All Architectures Welcome!

This temple seems like a junkyard of architectures, including the stone plinth resting on the original set of stairs.
By and large, the temples only go about 10 or 20 feet into the rock.  Unless you check for secret doors.

images.title: Recent Archaeology
images.description:
Recent Digs.

This area of engravings sits at the base of the rocky area around the Butterball. They recently dug down and found this riot of carvings.

images.title: Tiger Caves
images.description:
Tiger Caves

This little park is 10 minutes drive outside the town, another ancient temple site. We got here before 8AM, and had the entire place to ourselves.

images.title: Shore Temple Tourists
images.description:
Shore Temple Tourists

Indian tourists pay 50 cents. Foreigners pay 9 dollars.

images.title: Sunglasses
images.description:
Sunglasses

Sarah got her glasses in China when she went to meet with China Daily. Her China Daily chaperones explained the goal: the bigger the sunglasses, the smaller your face looks.
